==Latin==
===Etymology (1)===
Neuter gender form of [[fellaris]], adjective derived from [[fel]] “gall bladder.”

====Adjective====
'''fellare''' ''n'' 
# of, or relating to the [[gall bladder]]
# [[bitter]], [[poisonous]], [[venomous]]

===Etymology (2)===
Proto-Indo-European ''*dhē-lo-.''  

====Verb====
'''fell'''|'''[[Wiktionary Appendix:Latin first conjugation|ō, -āre, -āvī, -ātum]]'''
# To [[suck]].
# ''(vulgar)'' In particular, to [[fellate]].

====Derived terms====
* [[fellate]]
* [[fellatio]]

====Quotations====
* '''1st century AD,''' [[w:Martial|Martial]], ''Epigrams'' 2.50
*: Quod '''fellas''' et aquam potas, nil, Lesbia, peccas:
*:: qua tibi parte opus est, Lesbia, sumis aquam.
*: ''(Because you suck [cock] and drink water, Lesbia, you err in nothing:''
*:: ''in just the part you ought to be, Lesbia, you're making use of the water)''